The comment "randomly mixes" is in the NEW code added by the PR, which isn't on disk yet. Let me look at the diff more carefully to understand the serialization format.

From the diff, the DeletionVector.java code has these comments:
```java
// NOTE: the deletion vector randomly mixes big-endian and little-endian integers, so be very careful in this code
```

This is in both serialize() and deserialize() methods.

Let me re-analyze more carefully:

**Serialize (from the diff):**
```java
// write bodyLength (with reverseBytes)
slice.setInt(offset, Integer.reverseBytes(bodyLength));
offset += Integer.BYTES;

// write magic number (NO reverseBytes)
slice.setInt(offset, MAGIC_LE);
offset += Integer.BYTES;

// write bitmap count (NO reverseBytes, just getLong)
slice.setLong(offset, bitmapCount);
offset += SIZE_OF_LONG;
```

**Deserialize (from the diff):**
```java
// read length (with reverseBytes)
int length = Integer.reverseBytes(data.getInt(offset));
offset += Integer.BYTES;

// read magic number (NO reverseBytes)
int magicNumber = data.getInt(offset);
offset += Integer.BYTES;

// read bitmap count (NO reverseBytes, just getLong)
long bitmapCount = data.getLong(offset);
offset += SIZE_OF_LONG;
```

